Yup, that&#39;s mine.

It was generated from XML specifying informaiton about the run.  It
sounds like this would be a good option for you to use.

Philip and I have talked about breaking out the visualization tools
we&#39;re using as a separate entity, since they&#39;re
implementation-independent.  Currently we&#39;ve got style sheets that
generate visual output for:

--network layout
--fitness per generation throughout run
--complexity per generation throughout run (based on # of genes)
--species distribution throughout run

The last three style sheets all generate graphics based on run output
XML, so if you just wanted to use those tools, all you&#39;d need to do is
either spit out your run data into an XML file that looked something
like this:

&lt;?xml version = &quot;1.0&quot; encoding = &quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE run SYSTEM &quot;run.dtd&quot;&gt;
&lt;run id=&quot;1&quot; timedatestamp=&quot;120403&quot;&gt;
  &lt;parameters&gt;
    &lt;pop_size&gt;100&lt;/pop_size&gt;
    &lt;num_generations&gt;500&lt;/num_generations&gt;
    &lt;neuron_mut_rate&gt;0.1&lt;/neuron_mut_rate&gt;
    &lt;connect_mut_rate&gt;0.1&lt;/connect_mut_rate&gt;
    &lt;weight_mut_rate&gt;0.2&lt;/weight_mut_rate&gt;
    &lt;survival_rate&gt;0.2&lt;/survival_rate&gt;
  &lt;/parameters&gt; 
  &lt;generation num=&quot;1&quot;&gt;
    &lt;fitness&gt;
      &lt;max&gt;9875&lt;/max&gt;
      &lt;min&gt;10&lt;/min&gt;
      &lt;avg&gt;4520&lt;/avg&gt;
    &lt;/fitness&gt;
    &lt;species id=&quot;1&quot;&gt;
      &lt;count&gt;100&lt;/count&gt;
      &lt;fitness&gt;
        &lt;max&gt;9875&lt;/max&gt;
        &lt;min&gt;1752&lt;/min&gt;
        &lt;avg&gt;4520&lt;/avg&gt;
      &lt;/fitness&gt;
    &lt;/species&gt;
        &lt;species id=&quot;4&quot;&gt;
      &lt;count&gt;50&lt;/count&gt;
      &lt;fitness&gt;
        &lt;max&gt;9875&lt;/max&gt;
        &lt;min&gt;1752&lt;/min&gt;
        &lt;avg&gt;4520&lt;/avg&gt;
      &lt;/fitness&gt;
    &lt;/species&gt;
  &lt;/generation&gt;

Or spit it out in some other format, but have some code that
translates into the format above.

Colin has put together some samples of XML in the Files section.  Are
you using these formats for your implementation, Colin?  Have they
changed at all?  We hashed out a common XML format for networks...it
would be good to do the same for the run output.

I&#39;ll work on getting a website and repository up for the visualization
tools, and I&#39;m working on a decent user guide as well.  But in the
meantime, if you want to start using what we&#39;ve got in its current
state, just let me know and I&#39;ll send you what you need or post it to
the File section.

